title: For Sale:  Do you want a Saiga 12 ga?
postcontent:
Ok ladies and gentlemen, I usually just pass on the rants here and go shopping for guns.  I don’t like to get involved in the personal jabs that folks seem compelled to write.

But…this Saiga shotgun “craze has got me upset.  Everyone knows about the restrictions that are making these difficult to get – I understand that.  But are we collectively suffering from amnesia?
When the President was elected, everyone thought that ammo and guns would be taken away and a buying/hoarding frenzy erupted.  The world has no less steel, copper, and lead than it did 3 years ago but the demand drove prices through the roof.  

Same with the back rifles.  Everyone that ever thought of buying a gun ran out and emptied the shelves.  People charged outrageous prices for guns and ammo.  Lots of first-time shooters and collectors got taken for a really bad ride.  Anyone with a CNC started cranking out rifles so the supply caught up with the demand and eventually outran it.  What are the $2000 Bushmaster A-2’s worth now?

I just saw a Saiga in the box, unaltered, for $1000.  You all know that person paid about $600 for the thing.  Profit is okay – gouging is not and as such I will just move along.  He is fully entitled to make what the market will bear.  But are the consumers being wise and setting the price or are they just throwing money at the first Russian 12 ga. That whizzes bye?

How about these guns anyway?  Have we thought about what they are or why we want them?  Do that many of us use them in 3-gun?  Even the very top competitors say it takes at least $3000 to get them race-ready and reliable.  Are you going to make that investment?

How about home defense?  Have you shot a Saiga?  They are a lot of fun but not reliable and a terrible choice for defense.  A rock-solid Mossy or 870 can be had for under $300.  Gonna hunt with it?  I doubt it.  Will it improve your marksmanship skills?  The answer is no.  

There are as many of these shotguns around as there were a few months ago and they will go back down in price when the craze ends.  I just want to see you guys and gals ponder these points before you buy on impulse and are left wanting in the end.  Look at black rifles, ammo, beanie babies, tickle me elmo, cabbage patch kids and the list goes on.

Take a step back and ask yourself if these are really worth the price tag right now and if you really need one and can spare the money from your savings.  They are not good guns, mechanically,  and are not worth the price.  You will not likely make money on your investment and the gadgetry will wear off after about 100 shells.

Just be smart please and don’t get caught up in all this hype.   God bless, and be safe.

Thank you very much for your time.

title: For Sale:  Custom AR-15 rifle, accessories
location: New Port Richey, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
For sale is one of my favorite AR rifles.    It is built on a Denny's Guns special forged lower receiver - this is a thicker, stronger receiver than most ARs and has an adjustable screw in it to tighten up the mating of the upper and lower, taking out the "rattle" that is inherent in many ARs.  It has a nice Daniel Defense milspec set of internal lower parts including a nice worked 4 lb. trigger by Bill Springfield (Google him) (specially touched up, polished, new reduced power spring set), milspec bolt carrier group with upgraded extractor springs, black insert.  Magpul CTR milspec stock, H buffer and spring, Magpul MIAD grip with all the extra front and back straps, DPMS 1:7 twist M4 profile chrome lined barrel, A2 flashider, YHM Diamond freefloat handguards, Magpul MBUS front and rear backup sights, tactical charging handle.   It is a flat top so you can mount a red dot or magnified optic on it if you wish.  Also has an IKICKHIPPIES sling attachment point where the stock meets the lower receiver.

All furniture (stock, MIAD grip) is a nice OD green that looks great with the black of the rifle.

I've maybe put 400 rounds through it and it shoots great, even eating cheap Wolf ammo, though it prefers the brass stuff.  

Included is a folding bipod and attachment point.  Four 30-round black P-Mags with windows and Ranger plates attached, and one 20-round OD green Pmag.

More pics available upon request.
